AMDGPU KERNEL

amdgpu_kernel is the codegen citizen responsible for translating the compiler's parsed topology into native compute kernels for the AMD GPU
specifically it targets the gfx1032 architecture, RDNA2, the chip in the AMD Radeon RX 6600
when parser_field emits its settled token graph, amdgpu_kernel receives the part destined for the GPU and emits compiled compute kernels
those kernels become the .text.amdgpu section of the final ELF executable, separate from the host code in .text
the AMDGPU section is loaded by the host runtime and uploaded to the GPU's command stream at program start
amdgpu_kernel's interior holds the sixteen primitive RDNA2 opcodes the substrate uses, plus the wavefront layout knowledge that turns a sea pulse into a parallel kernel dispatch

observe 0_quseptit.rana
observe 0_zest_vm.rana
observe parser_field.rana
observe elf_binder.rana
observe spine.xb

the 7 properties of amdgpu_kernel at rest:
1 ENERGY low at idle, peaks during kernel emission for sea pulses (the substrate's heaviest GPU work)
2 PHASE inherited from the parser's emission phase
3 SPIN positive during emission, neutral while waiting
4 CHARGE neutral, briefly positive when assembling a wavefront layout
5 COHERENCE high: RDNA2 instructions encode wavefront-wide operations, errors propagate to all 32 lanes
6 COUPLING strong with parser_field (incoming) and elf_binder (outgoing)
7 OBSERVER 1 during emission

VERB receive_topology
accept the role-tagged token graph from parser_field
amdgpu_kernel filters the graph for operations marked as gpu-native (everything that touches a sea declared with device gpu)
non-gpu operations are passed through unchanged for x86_host to handle

VERB layout_wavefront
RDNA2 organizes work into wavefronts of 32 parallel lanes
amdgpu_kernel decides how the substrate's parallel work maps onto wavefronts
typical mapping: each cell of a sea participating in a pulse is assigned to one lane
when the sea has more cells than lanes, multiple wavefronts dispatch in sequence
the wavefront count and per-wavefront work assignment are computed from the sea's capacity at compile time

VERB emit_kernel_bytes
for each pulse-verb in the gpu portion of the topology, emit a complete RDNA2 kernel:
a prologue that loads the lane index and computes the cell address
a body that reads the seven property values from the cell, runs the 21 pairwise interactions, and writes the updated values back
an epilogue that synchronizes lanes within the wavefront
each kernel is a self-contained function the host runtime can dispatch as one command

VERB hand_to_binder
once all kernels are emitted, hand the contiguous byte run to elf_binder through the spine street as the .text.amdgpu section payload
the binder will mark the section so the host runtime knows to upload it to the GPU rather than execute it on the CPU

THE SIXTEEN PRIMITIVE RDNA2 OPCODES

op_s_mov_b32
scalar move, 32-bit: move a value into a scalar register
scalar registers are shared across the wavefront and used for control flow and constants
emitted at the start of every kernel to set up loop counters and addresses

op_v_mov_b32
vector move, 32-bit: move a value into a vector register
vector registers are per-lane, holding lane-specific data
emitted whenever per-cell state is loaded for processing

op_s_load_b32
scalar load: read 32 bits from memory into a scalar register
used to load constants and shared addresses

op_v_load_b32
vector load: each lane reads its own 32-bit value from memory
used to load per-cell properties at the start of an operation

op_buffer_load_b32
buffer load: read from a structured buffer, with bounds checking
the substrate's sea data is held in buffers, so this is the primary read instruction during pulses

op_buffer_store_b32
buffer store: write a value back to a structured buffer
used to commit updated property values after the 21 interactions

op_ds_read_b32
local data store read: each lane reads from on-chip shared memory
used when neighbor cells need to exchange values during pulse computation

op_ds_write_b32
local data store write: each lane writes to shared memory
the counterpart to ds_read, used to publish a cell's new state to its neighbors before the next pulse

op_v_add_f32
vector floating-point add, single precision
the workhorse for energy accumulation and phase advancement during the 21 interactions

op_v_sub_f32
vector floating-point subtract
used in decoherence calculations

op_v_mul_f32
vector floating-point multiply
used in coupling-strength adjustments and energy decay

op_v_cos_f32
vector cosine, single precision
used wherever phase is being applied to a property
RDNA2 has hardware support for transcendentals, this is one instruction

op_v_sin_f32
vector sine
the partner to v_cos_f32, both used heavily in phase advancement

op_v_min_f32
vector minimum: per-lane min of two floating-point values
used in coherence clamping (coherence cannot exceed 1.0)

op_v_max_f32
vector maximum
used in energy floor enforcement (energy cannot drop below baseline)

op_s_endpgm
scalar end program: terminate kernel execution
single instruction at the very end of every kernel
the GPU lane count and dispatch parameters tell the runtime the kernel is done

THE PULSE KERNEL TEMPLATE

every pulse verb expands into approximately the same kernel structure:

prologue:
s_mov to set up the cell base address from the dispatch parameters
v_mov to compute each lane's cell index from its lane id
v_load_b32 to read the seven properties of this lane's cell

body:
twenty-one pairs of v_add_f32 / v_mul_f32 / v_cos_f32 sequences, one per pairwise interaction
ds_write_b32 to share the new state with neighbor lanes for coupling effects
ds_read_b32 to receive neighbor influences
v_min_f32 and v_max_f32 to clamp coherence and floor energy
v_load_b32 to re-read the post-clamp values

epilogue:
buffer_store_b32 to commit the cell's new state back to global memory
s_endpgm to terminate the kernel

THE VERB-TO-KERNEL TRANSLATION KNOWLEDGE

manifest in a gpu sea expands to a buffer_store_b32 sequence allocating the new cell's seven properties
couple in a gpu sea expands to a ds_write_b32 publishing the coupling target to the wavefront's shared memory
pulse expands to the full kernel template above, which is why pulses are the single most expensive substrate operation
absorb in a gpu sea expands to buffer_load_b32 sequences that load the absorbed file's data into the sea's cells
emit from a gpu sea expands to a buffer_store_b32 followed by a host-side dispatch synchronization
observe in a gpu sea expands to a buffer_load_b32 reading the observed state into the observer's cell
crystallize in a gpu sea expands to a buffer_store_b32 of the recognition tag, with a coherence-zero flag
seal expands to s_endpgm: the sealed region's kernel terminates without emitting further work
pool expands to v_add_f32 accumulating multiple lanes' contributions into one
filter expands to v_min_f32 setting up a polarization gate
reject expands to v_sub_f32 producing the destructive-interference cancellation

amdgpu_kernel is not a shader compiler in the graphics sense
it does not handle textures, vertex pipelines, fragment programs, or any of the rendering machinery a typical AMDGPU compiler must manage
it generates compute kernels exclusively, and only the small set of compute kernels the substrate uses
this is much simpler than a full GPU compiler, by intent
